    <title>Differential Manifold and General relativity</title>
    <url>/2024/06/03/Math-test/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h2 id="Lengths-and-volumes"><a href="#Lengths-and-volumes" class="headerlink" title="Lengths and volumes"></a>Lengths and volumes</h2><p>Recall that dx→ has squared lengths </p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
ds^2=|\mathrm{g}_{\alpha \beta}dx^{\alpha}dx^{\beta}|</script><p>,integrate it gives the length of a curve：</p>
<span id="more"></span>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
l=\int_{\mathrm{curve}}{|\mathrm{g}_{\alpha \beta}dx^{\alpha}dx^{\beta}|}^{1/2}
\\
=\int_{\lambda _0}^{\lambda _1}{|\mathrm{g}_{\alpha \beta}\frac{dx^{\alpha}}{d\lambda}\frac{dx^{\beta}}{d\lambda}|^{1/2}}d\lambda 
\\
=\int_{\lambda _0}^{\lambda _1}{|\vec{V}\cdot \vec{V}|^{1/2}}d\lambda</script><p>Also,the computation of volumes is very important for integration in spacetime. Here, we mean by ‘volume’ the <strong>four-dimensional</strong> volume element we used for integrations in Gauss’law.</p>
<p>We know that we can write </p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
dx^0dx^1dx^2dx^3=\frac{\partial \left( x^0,x^1,x^2,x^3 \right)}{\partial \left( x^{0'},x^{1'},x^{2'},x^{3'} \right)}dx^{0'}dx^{1'}dx^{2'}dx^{3'}\tag{6}</script><p>The factor$\frac{\partial \left( x^0,x^1,x^2,x^3 \right)}{\partial \left( x^{0’},x^{1’},x^{2’},x^{3’} \right)}$is the <strong>Jacobian</strong> of the transformation from $\left\{ x^{\alpha’} \right\}$ to $\left\{ x^{\alpha} \right\}$  ,it is the same as </p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\frac{\partial \left( x^0,x^1,x^2,x^3 \right)}{\partial \left( x^{0'},x^{1'},x^{2'},x^{3'} \right)}=\det \left( \begin{matrix}
    \frac{\partial x^0}{\partial x^{0'}}&        \frac{\partial x^0}{\partial x^{1'}}&        \cdots\\
    \frac{\partial x^1}{\partial x^{0'}}&        \,\,&        \,\,\\
    \vdots&        \,\,&        \,\,\
\end{matrix} \right)=\det \left( {\Lambda ^{\alpha}}_{\beta '} \right)\tag{5}</script><p>Through analyzing the derivatives of general vectors we can obtain :</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\frac{\partial \vec{V}}{\partial x^{\beta}}=\frac{\partial V^{\alpha}}{\partial x^{\beta}}\vec{e}_{\alpha}+V^{\alpha}\frac{\partial \vec{e}_{\alpha}}{\partial x^{\beta}}\tag{9}\\</script><p>Notice that $\frac{\partial \vec{e}_{\alpha}}{\partial x^{\beta}}$</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
{V^{\alpha}}_{;\beta}={V^{\alpha}}_{,\beta}+V^{\mu}{\Gamma ^{\alpha}}_{\mu \beta}
\\
p_{\alpha ;\beta}=p_{\alpha ,\beta}-p_{\mu}{\Gamma ^{\mu}}_{\alpha \beta}\tag{10}</script>]]></content>
